column1: Whole Person Physiome Table for Female Reproductive System

List physiological functions as a hierarchy, starting with the body system in Function/1 (this should be the same as the table name), a major life function in Function/2, and more specific functions in subsequent columns. Add more columns if needed. Place limited explanatory text if needed in Function/Notes. Each function should include a ID from Gene Ontology (GO) if possible or another standard ontology. The LABEL column is the label for that ID as it appears in that ontology.
column26: Provide a very brief description (a few words) of the specific processes that occur during the corresponding function (e.g., a chemical reaction, physical change, feedback loop, etc.) in the Process column. Enter whether the Effector is a cell, tissue, or organ. Provide the anatomical location of the Effector in EffectorLocation along with the associated UBERON ID, if avaialble. Enter the Effector and its UBERON ID in the following columns. See Glossary for detailed instructions on tabulating the Signal, Effect, Behavior, Behavior X, Behavior Y, and X Target columns.

column73: REQUIRED. Enter references in support of the information on this row. The ID column should include a standard identifier, such as a DOI or ISBN. Add more sets of reference columns if needed, making sure to include the ID column.

column26: sperm fertilizes oocyte in ampulla of fallopian tube
morula forms approximately 3 days after fertilization, remains in ampulla until blastocyst stage
blastocyst implants in endometrium 6-7 days post-fertilization
endometrial stromal cells change into rounded decidual cells, beginning near the spiral arteries
trophoblast of blastocyst secretes beta hcg to maintain iniital pregnancy, sustains corpus luteum as maternal LH decreases
syncytiotrophoblast becomes main component of maternal-fetal interface
cytotrophoblast will penetrate syncytiotrophoblast and form chorionic villi
invasion of syncytiotrophoblast into maternal endometrium begins the formation of the placenta
blood volume increases by ~45% in pregnancy (~50% bump in plasma, ~33% increase in erythrocytes, leading to dilutional anemia)
cardiac output increases 35-45% in pregnancy
alveolar ventilation (via tidal volume) increases ~45%
gravid uterus grows and expands via myometrial hypertrophy to accomodate the growing fetus
myometrium undergoes genetic expression changes leading to increased expression of connexin-43, receptors for prostaglandins, and oxytocin
cervix increases transcription of genes such as collagenases to facilitate effacement and dilation
oxytocin and prostaglandins cause coordinated and rhythmic uterine contraction
contraction and pushing of fetal head against cervix leads to progressive cervical dilation
oxytocin drives further uterine contraction to cause constriction of the spiral arteries and delivery of the placenta
placenta is delivered from the uterus through the vagina
